-1 404 "N.B.  There are various questions and properties about prime n
umbers which are of interest and study.  For example, it is known that
 there are infinitely many primes.  There is only one even prime. (Why
?)  The distribution of the odd primes is not fully understood.  If tw
o consecutive odd numbers are both prime (e.g., (5,7) ; (17,19), (101,
103)), then such a pair of consecutive odd primes is called a " }
{TEXT 279 19 "pair of twin primes" }{TEXT -1 174 ".  It is not known w
hether or not there are infinitely many such pairs of twin primes.  It
 is known that there can be arbitrarily large gaps between consecutive
 primes.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 372 "5.  Relatively Prime Numbers.  Two positive integers are
 said to be relatively prime if the only positive integer which (evenl
y) divides both of them is 1.  Examples of  (pairs of) relatively prim
e integers are:  74, 51;   13, 120;   344280, 267317.  If two integers
 are relatively prime, then the greatest common divisor of the two int
egers must be 1.  The maple command " }{TEXT 275 3 "gcd" }{TEXT -1 
296 " can be used to determine whether greatest common divisor of two \+
integers is 1, i.e., whether the two integers are relatively prime.  S
how that each of the above mentioned pairs of integers are relatively \+
prime.  Find three other pairs of relatively prime integers with the f
ollowing constraints:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 72 "(a) neither inte
ger is itself prime; (b) each integer is more than 1000." }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 95 "ispri
me (1010);\nisprime (1004);\nisprime (1005);\nisprime (1006);\nisprime
 (1007);\nisprime (1011);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%&falseG
